Your Honor,

I, David Lambert, stand before this honorable court to express my deep remorse for driving while disqualified. At the age of 55, I have maintained a clean criminal record, aside from my recent disqualification resulting from four speeding incidents. Regrettably, I failed to exercise sound judgment when I disregarded the court's order and made the ill-advised decision to drive to a nearby supermarket.

I am sincerely sorry for my actions and I acknowledge that they were an affront to the court's authority. I fully understand the gravity of my lapse in judgment and apologize for not adhering to the court's instructions. It was irresponsible and thoughtless of me to overlook the fact that I was disqualified from driving.

Recognizing the seriousness of my offense, I have taken immediate responsibility for my actions by pleading guilty to driving while disqualified. I understand that my guilty plea is a positive step towards acknowledging the severity of the offense and demonstrating my willingness to make amends.

In light of this incident, I have gained a profound appreciation for the importance of adhering to traffic laws and court orders. As such, I humbly request the court's guidance and support in enabling me to rehabilitate myself. I am committed to actively participating in educational programs or courses that will deepen my understanding of traffic laws and reinforce the significance of complying with court orders.

I approach this court with utmost humility and with the firm belief that this experience has compelled me to evaluate my choices and strive to be a responsible member of society. I am dedicated to personal growth and committed to becoming a law-abiding citizen who contributes positively to the community.

I respectfully ask for leniency from the court as I embark on this path of rehabilitation and self-improvement. I assure Your Honor that I understand the impact of my actions on society and pledge to make meaningful efforts to rectify the harm caused.

Thank you for your attention and consideration.

Respectfully,
David Lambert
